comments.body:
If it can be positively identified it would be The first positive identification I know in southern Ontario Exciting!! So Iâ€™m definitely interested in figuring this out and I have a picture of a wood frog the same day  with different makings but need a specialist.  
Thanks for you help.
Iâ€™m a bit too far away right now, sorry. I wish I could come, that sounds like a great spot. The area sounds great for salamanders, Iâ€™m sure youâ€™ll find one soon.

This is a private deciduous forest with a large swamp recognized by the Ministry of natural resources. finding a salamander in my area would be like finding the holy grail. If youâ€™re close I could take you into this area if interested

Thanks ! I was looking for salamanders the other day and got three (two redback, one bluespot). I wonder if I might stumble upon a chorus frog if I head back there. Were the trees in your area deciduous or coniferous? I'm guessing the chorus frogs would prefer deciduous but I'm not sure.

Itâ€™s a  dry swamp at this time of the year. Mature trees with lots of rotting logs you start lifting some of the old rotting logs youâ€™re sure to find some.or something. I was actually looking for salamanders PS we have no poisonous snakes. Having fun frogging
Also, do you think you could describe the conditions in which you found this frog, please? I'd really like to find a chorus frog this autumn, so it'd be nice to know how other people found theirs
